#Text=CHAPTER
#Text=V
#Text=“ Stern Lawgiver ! yet thou dost wear The Godhead ’s most benignant grace ;
#Text=Nor know we anything so fair
#Text=As is the smile upon thy face :
#Text=Flowers laugh before thee on their beds
#Text=And fragrance in thy footing treads ; Thou dost preserve the stars from wrong ;
#Text=And the most ancient heavens , through Thee , are fresh and strong . ”
#Text=WORDSWORTH , Ode to Duty .
#Text=[ Picture : Dog and cat ]
#Text=BUT what became of little Tom ?
#Text=He slipped away off the rocks into the water , as I said before .
#Text=But he could not help thinking of little Ellie .
#Text=He did not remember who she was ; but he knew that she was a little girl , though she was a hundred times as big as he .
#Text=That is not surprising : size has nothing to do with kindred .
#Text=A tiny weed may be first cousin to a great tree ; and a little dog like Vick knows that Lioness is a dog too , though she is twenty times larger than herself .
#Text=So Tom knew that Ellie was a little girl , and thought about her all that day , and longed to have had her to play with ; but he had very soon to think of something else .

#Text=And here is the account of what happened to him , as it was published next morning , in the Water-proof Gazette , on the finest watered paper , for the use of the great fairy , Mrs. Bedonebyasyoudid , who reads the news very carefully every morning , and especially the police cases , as you will hear very soon .

#Text=He was going along the rocks in three-fathom water , watching the pollock catch prawns , and the wrasses nibble barnacles off the rocks , shells and all , when he saw a round cage of green withes ; and inside it , looking very much ashamed of himself , sat his friend the lobster , twiddling his horns , instead of thumbs .
#Text=[ Picture : Tom , the lobster and otter ]
#Text=“ What , have you been naughty , and have they put you in the lock-up ? ” asked Tom .
#Text=The lobster felt a little indignant at such a notion , but he was too much depressed in spirits to argue ; so he only said , “ I ca n’t get out . ”
#Text=“ Why did you get in ? ”
#Text=“ After that nasty piece of dead fish . ”
#Text=He had thought it looked and smelt very nice when he was outside , and so it did , for a lobster : but now he turned round and abused it because he was angry with himself .
#Text=“ Where did you get in ? ”
#Text=“ Through that round hole at the top . ”
#Text=“ Then why do n’t you get out through it ? ”
#Text=“ Because I ca n’t : ” and the lobster twiddled his horns more fiercely than ever , but he was forced to confess .
#Text=“ I have jumped upwards , downwards , backwards , and sideways , at least four thousand times ; and I ca n’t get out : I always get up underneath there , and ca n’t find the hole . ”
#Text=Tom looked at the trap , and having more wit than the lobster , he saw plainly enough what was the matter ; as you may if you will look at a lobster-pot .
#Text=“ Stop a bit , ” said Tom .
#Text=“ Turn your tail up to me , and I ’ll pull you through hindforemost , and then you wo n’t stick in the spikes . ”
#Text=But the lobster was so stupid and clumsy that he could n’t hit the hole .

#Text=Like a great many fox-hunters , he was very sharp as long as he was in his own country ; but as soon as they get out of it they lose their heads ; and so the lobster , so to speak , lost his tail .
#Text=Tom reached and clawed down the hole after him , till he caught hold of him ; and then , as was to be expected , the clumsy lobster pulled him in head foremost .
#Text=“ Hullo ! here is a pretty business , ” said Tom .
#Text=“ Now take your great claws , and break the points off those spikes , and then we shall both get out easily . ”
#Text=“ Dear me , I never thought of that , ” said the lobster ;
#Text=“ and after all the experience of life that I have had ! ”
#Text=You see , experience is of very little good unless a man , or a lobster , has wit enough to make use of it .
#Text=For a good many people , like old Polonius , have seen all the world , and yet remain little better than children after all .
#Text=But they had not got half the spikes away when they saw a great dark cloud over them : and lo , and behold , it was the otter .
#Text=How she did grin and grin when she saw Tom .
#Text=“ Yar ! ” said she , “ you little meddlesome wretch , I have you now ! I will serve you out for telling the salmon where I was ! ” And she crawled all over the pot to get in .
#Text=Tom was horribly frightened , and still more frightened when she found the hole in the top , and squeezed herself right down through it , all eyes and teeth .
#Text=But no sooner was her head inside than valiant Mr. Lobster caught her by the nose and held on .
#Text=And there they were all three in the pot , rolling over and over , and very tight packing it was .

#Text=And the lobster tore at the otter , and the otter tore at the lobster , and both squeezed and thumped poor Tom till he had no breath left in his body ; and I do n’t know what would have happened to him if he had not at last got on the otter ’s back , and safe out of the hole .
